p.name: MSK_IPAR_SIM_DUAL_RESTRICT_SELECTION
p.cmnt:
The dual simplex optimizer can use a so-called restricted selection/pricing strategy to chooses the outgoing variable. Hence, if restricted selection is applied, then the dual simplex optimizer first choose a subset of all the potential outgoing variables. Next, for some time it will choose the outgoing variable only among the subset. From time to time the subset is redefined.
A larger value of this parameter implies that the optimizer will be more aggressive in its restriction strategy, i.e. a value of 0 implies that the restriction strategy is not applied at all.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_MIO_CUT_LEVEL_ROOT

%inline the file "../shared/miocutlevel.tex" \begin{tabular}{ll} GUB cover & +2\\ Flow cover & +4 \\ Lifting & +8 \\ Plant location & +16\\ Disaggregation & +32\\ Knapsack cover & +64\\ Lattice & +128\\ Gomory & +256\\ Coefficient reduction & +512\\ GCD & +1024 \\ Obj. integrality & +2048\\ \end{tabular}

p.cmnt: Controls whether the mixed-integer presolve performs probing. Probing can be very time consuming.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_INFEAS_PREFER_PRIMAL
p.cmnt: If both certificates of primal and dual infeasibility are supplied then only the primal is used when this option is turned on.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_WRITE_IGNORE_INCOMPATIBLE_NL_ITEMS
p.cmnt: Controls if the writer ignores general non-linear terms or produces an error.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_WRITE_BAS_VARIABLES
p.cmnt: Controls whether the variables section is written to the basic solution file.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_LOG_STORAGE
p.cmnt: When turned on, \mosek{} prints messages regarding the storage usage and allocation.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_MIO_PRESOLVE_USE
p.cmnt: Controls whether presolve is performed by the mixed-integer optimizer.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_READ_LP_QUOTED_NAMES
p.cmnt: If a name is in quotes when reading an LP file, the quotes will be removed.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_INTPNT_BASIS
p.cmnt: Controls whether the interior-point optimizer also computes an optimal basis.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_LOG_CUT_SECOND_OPT
p.cmnt: If a task is employed to solve a sequence of optimization problems, then the value of the log levels is reduced by the value of this parameter. E.g \mskitem{iparam.log} and \mskitem{iparam.log_sim} are reduced by the value of this parameter for the second and any subsequent optimizations.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_READ_MPS_KEEP_INT
p.cmnt: Controls whether \mosek{} should keep the integer restrictions on the variables while reading the MPS file.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_MIO_MAX_NUM_SOLUTIONS
p.cmnt: The mixed-integer optimizer can be terminated after a certain number of different feasible solutions has been located. If this parameter has the value $n$ and $n$ is strictly positive, then the mixed-integer optimizer will be terminated when $n$ feasible solutions have been located.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_READ_DEBUG
p.cmnt: Turns on additional debugging information when reading files.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_WRITE_SOL_VARIABLES
p.cmnt: Controls whether the variables section is written to the solution file.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_SENSITIVITY_OPTIMIZER
p.cmnt: Controls which optimizer is used for optimal partition sensitivity analysis.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_WRITE_MPS_INT
p.cmnt: Controls if marker records are written to the MPS file to indicate whether variables are integer restricted.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_LICENSE_WAIT
p.cmnt: If all licenses are in use \mosek{} returns with an error code. However, by turning on this parameter \mosek{} will wait for an available license.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_CONCURRENT_PRIORITY_FREE_SIMPLEX
p.cmnt: Priority of the free simplex optimizer when selecting solvers for concurrent optimization.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_READ_KEEP_FREE_CON
p.cmnt: Controls whether the free constraints are included in the problem.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_LOG_FILE
p.cmnt: If turned on, then some log info is printed when a file is written or read.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_CONCURRENT_PRIORITY_INTPNT
p.cmnt: Priority of the interior-point algorithm when selecting solvers for concurrent optimization.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_SIM_NON_SINGULAR
p.cmnt: Controls if the simplex optimizer ensures a non-singular basis, if possible.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_WRITE_DATA_PARAM
p.cmnt: If this option is turned on the parameter settings are written to the data file as parameters.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_SIM_DEGEN
p.cmnt: Controls how aggressively degeneration is handled.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_OPF_WRITE_HINTS
p.cmnt: Write a hint section with problem dimensions in the beginning of an OPF file.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_PRESOLVE_ELIMINATOR_USE
p.cmnt: Controls whether free or implied free variables are eliminated from the problem.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_ALLOC_ADD_QNZ
p.cmnt: Additional number of $Q$ non-zeros that are allocated space for when \comp{numanz} exceeds \comp{maxnumqnz} during addition of new $Q$ entries.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_MIO_HOTSTART
p.cmnt: Controls whether the integer optimizer is hot-started.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_READ_MPS_FORMAT
p.cmnt: Controls how strictly the MPS file reader interprets the MPS format.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_PARAM_READ_CASE_NAME
p.cmnt: If turned on, then names in the parameter file are case sensitive.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_LOG_OPTIMIZER
p.cmnt: Controls the amount of general optimizer information that is logged.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_MIO_MAX_NUM_BRANCHES
p.cmnt: Maximum number of branches allowed during the branch and bound search. A negative value means infinite.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_SIM_PRIMAL_CRASH
p.cmnt:
Controls whether crashing is performed in the primal simplex optimizer.
In general, if a basis consists of more than (100-this parameter value)\% fixed variables, then a crash will be performed.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_MIO_CONSTRUCT_SOL
p.cmnt: If set to \mskitem{onoffkey.on} and all integer variables have been given a value for which a feasible mixed integer solution exists, then \mosek{} generates an initial solution to the mixed integer problem by fixing all integer values and solving the remaining problem.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_AUTO_SORT_A_BEFORE_OPT
p.cmnt: Controls whether the elements in each column of $A$ are sorted before an optimization is performed. This is not required but makes the optimization more deterministic.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_MIO_STRONG_BRANCH
p.cmnt: The value specifies the depth from the root in which strong branching is used. A negative value means that the optimizer chooses a default value automatically.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_SIM_DUAL_PHASEONE_METHOD
p.cmnt: An exprimental feature.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_SIM_INTEGER
p.cmnt: An exprimental feature.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_MIO_USE_MULTITHREADED_OPTIMIZER
p.cmnt: Controls wheter the new multithreaded optimizer should be used for Mixed integer problems.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_SIM_PRIMAL_RESTRICT_SELECTION
p.cmnt:
The primal simplex optimizer can use a so-called restricted selection/pricing strategy to chooses the outgoing variable. Hence, if restricted selection is applied, then the primal simplex optimizer first choose a subset of all the potential incoming variables. Next, for some time it will choose the incoming variable only among the subset. From time to time the subset is redefined.
A larger value of this parameter implies that the optimizer will be more aggressive in its restriction strategy, i.e. a value of 0 implies that the restriction strategy is not applied at all.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_READ_CONE
p.cmnt: Expected maximum number of conic constraints to be read. The option is used only by fast MPS and LP file readers.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_OPTIMIZER
p.cmnt: The paramter controls which optimizer is used to optimize the task.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_MAX_NUM_WARNINGS
p.cmnt: A negtive number means all warnings are logged. Otherwise the parameter specifies the maximum number times each warning is logged.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_LICENSE_SUPPRESS_EXPIRE_WRNS
p.cmnt: Controls whether license features expire warnings are suppressed.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_MIO_CUT_CG
p.cmnt: Controls whether CG cuts should be generated.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_WRITE_SOL_IGNORE_INVALID_NAMES
p.cmnt: Even if the names are invalid MPS names, then they are employed when writing the solution file.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_WRITE_SOL_HEAD
p.cmnt: Controls whether the header section is written to the solution file.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_WRITE_BAS_CONSTRAINTS
p.cmnt: Controls whether the constraint section is written to the basic solution file.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_LOG_EXPAND
p.cmnt: Controls the amount of logging when a data item such as the maximum number constrains is expanded.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_MIO_FEASPUMP_LEVEL
p.cmnt: Feasibility pump is a heuristic designed to compute an initial feasible solution. A value of 0 implies that the feasibility pump heuristic is not used. A value of -1 implies that the mixed-integer optimizer decides how the feasibility pump heuristic is used. A larger value than 1 implies that the feasibility pump is employed more aggressively. Normally a value beyond 3 is not worthwhile.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_INFEAS_GENERIC_NAMES
p.cmnt: Controls whether generic names are used when an infeasible subproblem is created.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_LOG_RESPONSE
p.cmnt: Controls amount of output printed when response codes are reported. A higher level implies that more information is logged.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_LOG
p.cmnt:
Controls the amount of log information. The value 0 implies that all log information is suppressed. A higher level implies that more information is logged.
Please note that if a task is employed to solve a sequence of optimization problems the value of this parameter is reduced by the value of \mskitem{iparam.log_cut_second_opt} for the second and any subsequent optimizations.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_INFEAS_REPORT_LEVEL
p.cmnt: Controls the amount of information presented in an infeasibility report. Higher values imply more information.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_WRITE_DATA_COMPRESSED
p.cmnt: Controls whether the data file is compressed while it is written. $0$ means no compression while higher values mean more compression.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_SIM_SWITCH_OPTIMIZER
p.cmnt: The simplex optimizer sometimes chooses to solve the dual problem instead of the primal problem. This implies that if you have chosen to use the dual simplex optimizer and the problem is dualized, then it actually makes sense to use the primal simplex optimizer instead. If this parameter is on and the problem is dualized and furthermore the simplex optimizer is chosen to be the primal (dual) one, then it is switched to the dual (primal).

p.name: MSK_IPAR_READ_DATA_COMPRESSED
p.cmnt: If this option is turned on,it is assumed that the data file is compressed.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_SOL_FILTER_KEEP_RANGED
p.cmnt: If turned on, then ranged constraints and variables are written to the solution file independent of the filter setting.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_OPF_WRITE_PROBLEM
p.cmnt: Write objective, constraints, bounds etc. to an OPF file.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_NUM_THREADS
p.cmnt: Controls the number of threads employed by the optimizer. If set to 0 the number of threads used will be equal to the number of cores detected on the machine.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_LOG_CHECK_CONVEXITY
p.cmnt:
Controls logging in convexity check on quadratic problems. Set to a positive value to turn logging on.
If a quadratic coefficient matrix is found to violate the requirement of PSD (NSD) then a list of negative (positive) pivot elements is printed. The absolute value of the pivot elements is also shown.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_READ_DATA_FORMAT
p.cmnt: Format of the data file to be read.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_SIM_DUAL_CRASH
p.cmnt:
Controls whether crashing is performed in the dual simplex optimizer.
In general if a basis consists of more than (100-this parameter value)\% fixed variables, then a crash will be performed.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_READ_VAR
p.cmnt: Expected maximum number of variable to be read. The option is used only by MPS and LP file readers.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_LOG_HEAD
p.cmnt: If turned on, then a header line is added to the log.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_SIM_REFORMULATION
p.cmnt: Controls if the simplex optimizers are allowed to reformulate the problem.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_SIM_SAVE_LU
p.cmnt: Controls if the LU factorization stored should be replaced with the LU factorization corresponding to the initial basis.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_INTPNT_FACTOR_METHOD
p.cmnt: Controls the method used to factor the Newton equation system.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_MIO_MAX_NUM_RELAXS
p.cmnt: Maximum number of relaxations allowed during the branch and bound search. A negative value means infinite.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_SOL_FILTER_KEEP_BASIC
p.cmnt: If turned on, then basic and super basic constraints and variables are written to the solution file independent of the filter setting.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_MIO_HEURISTIC_LEVEL
p.cmnt: Controls the heuristic employed by the mixed-integer optimizer to locate an initial good integer feasible solution. A value of zero means the heuristic is not used at all. A larger value than 0 means that a gradually more sophisticated heuristic is used which is computationally more expensive. A negative value implies that the optimizer chooses the heuristic. Normally a value around $3$ to $5$ should be optimal.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_MIO_KEEP_BASIS
p.cmnt: Controls whether the integer presolve keeps bases in memory. This speeds on the solution process at cost of bigger memory consumption.

p.name: MSK_IPAR_INTPNT_SCALING
p.cmnt: Controls how the problem is scaled before the interior-point optimizer is used.

c.name: MSK_BK_FR

c.name: MSK_BK_UP

c.name: MSK_BK_RA
c.cmnt: The constraint or variable is ranged.

c.name: MSK_BI_ALWAYS
c.cmnt: Basis identification is always performed even if the interior-point optimizer terminates abnormally.

c.name: MSK_BI_NO_ERROR
c.cmnt: Basis identification is performed if the interior-point optimizer terminates without an error.

c.name: MSK_BI_NEVER
c.cmnt: Never do basis identification.

c.name: MSK_BI_IF_FEASIBLE
c.cmnt: Basis identification is not performed if the interior-point optimizer terminates with a problem status saying that the problem is primal or dual infeasible.

c.name: MSK_BI_RESERVERED

c.name: MSK_BRANCH_DIR_DOWN
c.cmnt: The mixed-integer optimizer always chooses the down branch first.

c.name: MSK_BRANCH_DIR_UP
c.cmnt: The mixed-integer optimizer always chooses the up branch first.

c.name: MSK_BRANCH_DIR_FREE
c.cmnt: The mixed-integer optimizer decides which branch to choose.

c.name: MSK_LIINF_INTPNT_FACTOR_NUM_NZ
c.cmnt: Number of non-zeros in factorization.

c.name: MSK_LIINF_BI_DUAL_ITER
c.cmnt: Number of dual pivots performed in the basis identification.

c.name: MSK_LIINF_BI_CLEAN_DUAL_DEG_ITER
c.cmnt: Number of dual degenerate clean iterations performed in the basis identification.

c.name: MSK_LIINF_BI_CLEAN_PRIMAL_DUAL_SUB_ITER
c.cmnt: Number of primal-dual subproblem clean iterations performed in the basis identification.

c.name: MSK_STREAM_ERR

c.name: MSK_RES_TRM_STALL
c.cmnt:
The optimizer is terminated due to slow progress.
Stalling means that numerical problems prevent the optimizer from making reasonable progress and that it make no sense to continue. In many cases this happens if the problem is badly scaled or otherwise ill-conditioned. There is no guarantee that the solution will be (near) feasible or near optimal. However, often stalling happens near the optimum, and the returned solution may be of good quality. Therefore, it is recommended to check the status of then solution. If the solution near optimal the solution is most likely good enough for most practical purposes.
Please note that if a linear optimization problem is solved using the interior-point optimizer with basis identification turned on, the returned basic solution likely to have high accuracy, even though the optimizer stalled.
Some common causes of stalling are a) badly scaled models, b) near feasible or near infeasible problems and c) a non-convex problems. Case c) is only relevant for general non-linear problems. It is not possible in general for \mosek to check if a specific problems is convex since such a check would be NP hard in itself. This implies that care should be taken when solving problems involving general user defined functions.

p.cmnt: This parameter limits the maximum time spent by the mixed-integer optimizer. A negative number means infinity.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_BASIS_TOL_S
p.cmnt: Maximum absolute dual bound violation in an optimal basic solution.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_PRESOLVE_TOL_S
p.cmnt: Absolute zero tolerance employed for $s_i$ in the presolve.

p.cmnt: If either a primal or dual feasible solution is found proving that the optimal objective value is outside, [\mskitem{dparam.lower_obj_cut}, \mskitem{dparam.upper_obj_cut}], then \mosek{} is terminated.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_CO_TOL_DFEAS
p.cmnt: Dual feasibility tolerance used by the conic interior-point optimizer.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_DATA_TOL_AIJ_LARGE
p.cmnt: An element in $A$ which is larger than this value in absolute size causes a warning message to be printed.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_MIO_TOL_ABS_GAP
p.cmnt: Absolute optimality tolerance employed by the mixed-integer optimizer.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_UPPER_OBJ_CUT_FINITE_TRH
p.cmnt: If the upper objective cut is greater than the value of this value parameter, then the the upper objective cut \mskitem{dparam.upper_obj_cut} is treated as $\infty$.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_MIO_TOL_ABS_RELAX_INT
p.cmnt: Absolute relaxation tolerance of the integer constraints. I.e. $\min(|x|-\lfloor x \rfloor,\lceil x \rceil - |x|)$ is less than the tolerance then the integer restrictions assumed to be satisfied.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_NONCONVEX_TOL_OPT
p.cmnt: Optimality tolerance used by the nonconvex optimizer.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_NONCONVEX_TOL_FEAS
p.cmnt: Feasibility tolerance used by the nonconvex optimizer.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_MIO_TOL_MAX_CUT_FRAC_RHS
p.cmnt: Maximum value of fractional part of right hand side to generate CMIR and CG cuts for. A value of $0.0$ means that the value is selected automatically.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_SIMPLEX_ABS_TOL_PIV
p.cmnt: Absolute pivot tolerance employed by the simplex optimizers.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_MIO_TOL_REL_DUAL_BOUND_IMPROVEMENT
p.cmnt: If the relative improvement of the dual bound is smaller than this value, the solver will terminate the root cut generation. A value of $0.0$ means that the value is selected automatically.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_MIO_HEURISTIC_TIME
p.cmnt: Minimum amount of time to be used in the heuristic search for a good feasible integer solution. A negative values implies that the optimizer decides the amount of time to be spent in the heuristic.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_CHECK_CONVEXITY_REL_TOL
p.cmnt:
This parameter controls when the full convexity check declares a problem to be non-convex. Increasing this tolerance relaxes the criteria for declaring the problem non-convex.
A problem is declared non-convex if negative (positive) pivot elements are detected in the cholesky factor of a matrix which is required to be PSD (NSD). This parameter controles how much this non-negativity requirement may be violated.
If $d_i$ is the pivot element for column $i$, then the matrix $Q$ is considered to not be PSD if: \[ d_i \leq - |Q_{ii}| * \mathtt{check\_convexity\_rel\_tol} \]

p.name: MSK_DPAR_PRESOLVE_TOL_X
p.cmnt: Absolute zero tolerance employed for $x_j$ in the presolve.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_NL_TOL_MU_RED
p.cmnt: Relative complementarity gap tolerance.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_MIO_NEAR_TOL_REL_GAP
p.cmnt: The mixed-integer optimizer is terminated when this tolerance is satisfied. This termination criteria is delayed. See \mskitem{dparam.mio_disable_term_time} for details.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_MIO_TOL_MIN_CUT_FRAC_RHS
p.cmnt: Minimum value of fractional part of right hand side to generate CMIR and CG cuts for. A value of $0.0$ means that the value is selected automatically.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_PRESOLVE_TOL_REL_LINDEP
p.cmnt: Relative tolerance employed by the linear dependency checker.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_DATA_TOL_AIJ
p.cmnt: Absolute zero tolerance for elements in $A$. If any value $A_{ij}$ is smaller than this parameter in absolute terms MOSEK will treat the values as zero and generate a warning.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_FEASREPAIR_TOL
p.cmnt: Tolerance for constraint enforcing upper bound on sum of weighted violations in feasibility repair.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_TOL_DSAFE
p.cmnt: Controls the initial dual starting point used by the interior-point optimizer. If the interior-point optimizer converges slowly.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_MIO_TOL_FEAS
p.cmnt: Feasibility tolerance for mixed integer solver. Any solution with maximum infeasibility below this value will be considered feasible.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_TOL_INFEAS
p.cmnt: Controls when the optimizer declares the model primal or dual infeasible. A small number means the optimizer gets more conservative about declaring the model infeasible.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_NL_TOL_NEAR_REL
p.cmnt: If the \mosek{} nonlinear interior-point optimizer cannot compute a solution that has the prescribed accuracy, then it will multiply the termination tolerances with value of this parameter. If the solution then satisfies the termination criteria, then the solution is denoted near optimal, near feasible and so forth.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_OPTIMIZER_MAX_TIME
p.cmnt: Maximum amount of time the optimizer is allowed to spent on the optimization. A negative number means infinity.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_DATA_TOL_X
p.cmnt: Zero tolerance for constraints and variables i.e. if the distance between the lower and upper bound is less than this value, then the lower and lower bound is considered identical.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_ANA_SOL_INFEAS_TOL
p.cmnt: If a constraint violates its bound with an amount larger than this value, the constraint name, index and violation will be printed by the solution analyzer.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_MIO_REL_ADD_CUT_LIMITED
p.cmnt: Controls how many cuts the mixed-integer optimizer is allowed to add to the problem. Let $\alpha$ be the value of this parameter and $m$ the number constraints, then mixed-integer optimizer is allowed to $\alpha m$ cuts.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_TOL_MU_RED
p.cmnt: Relative complementarity gap tolerance.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_CO_TOL_MU_RED
p.cmnt: Relative complementarity gap tolerance feasibility tolerance used by the conic interior-point optimizer.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_CO_TOL_REL_GAP
p.cmnt: Relative gap termination tolerance used by the conic interior-point optimizer.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_LOWER_OBJ_CUT

p.name: MSK_DPAR_MIO_TOL_X
p.cmnt: Absolute solution tolerance used in mixed-integer optimizer.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_DATA_TOL_C_HUGE
p.cmnt: An element in $c$ which is larger than the value of this parameter in absolute terms is considered to be huge and generates an error.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_SIM_LU_TOL_REL_PIV
p.cmnt:
Relative pivot tolerance employed when computing the LU factorization of the basis in the simplex optimizers and in the basis identification procedure.
A value closer to $1.0$ generally improves numerical stability but typically also implies an increase in the computational work.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_DATA_TOL_CJ_LARGE

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_TOL_STEP_SIZE
p.cmnt: If the step size falls below the value of this parameter, then the interior-point optimizer assumes that it is stalled. In other words the interior-point optimizer does not make any progress and therefore it is better stop.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_TOL_PFEAS
p.cmnt: Primal feasibility tolerance used for linear and quadratic optimization problems.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_BASIS_REL_TOL_S
p.cmnt: Maximum relative dual bound violation allowed in an optimal basic solution.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_PRESOLVE_TOL_ABS_LINDEP
p.cmnt: Absolute tolerance employed by the linear dependency checker.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_CO_TOL_INFEAS
p.cmnt: Controls when the conic interior-point optimizer declares the model primal or dual infeasible. A small number means the optimizer gets more conservative about declaring the model infeasible.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_MIO_REL_GAP_CONST

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_TOL_PATH
p.cmnt: Controls how close the interior-point optimizer follows the central path. A large value of this parameter means the central is followed very closely. On numerical unstable problems it may be worthwhile to increase this parameter.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_NL_MERIT_BAL
p.cmnt: Controls if the complementarity and infeasibility is converging to zero at about equal rates.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_BASIS_TOL_X
p.cmnt: Maximum absolute primal bound violation allowed in an optimal basic solution.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_TOL_REL_GAP
p.cmnt: Relative gap termination tolerance.

p.name: MSK_DPAR_DATA_TOL_AIJ_HUGE

p.name: MSK_DPAR_INTPNT_TOL_DFEAS

p.name: MSK_DPAR_MIO_TOL_REL_RELAX_INT
